For a regular 7-gon, the angles between vertices are multiples of \(2\pi/7\), leading to angles \(\pi/7\), \(2\pi/7\), and \(3\pi/7\). The lengths corresponding to these angles are \(2 \sin(\pi/7)\), \(2 \sin(2\pi/7)\), and \(2 \sin(3\pi/7)\). Each length occurs 7 times, so the sum we need is: \[ 7 \left( [2 \sin(\pi/7)]^4 + [2 \sin(2\pi/7)]^4 + [2 \sin(3\pi/7)]^4 \right) \] Simplifying, this becomes: \[ 112 \left( \sin^4(\pi/7) + \sin^4(2\pi/7) + \sin^4(3\pi/7) \right) \] Using the trigonometric identity \(\sin^4(x) = \frac{3 - 4\cos(2x) + \cos(4x)}{8}\), we convert each term: \[ \sin^4(\pi/7) = \frac{3 - 4\cos(2\pi/7) + \cos(4\pi/7)}{8} \] \[ \sin^4(2\pi/7) = \frac{3 - 4\cos(4\pi/7) + \cos(8\pi/7)}{8} \] \[ \sin^4(3\pi/7) = \frac{3 - 4\cos(6\pi/7) + \cos(12\pi/7)}{8} \] Summing these, we get: \[ \frac{1}{8} \left( 9 - 4[\cos(2\pi/7) + \cos(4\pi/7) + \cos(6\pi/7)] + [\cos(4\pi/7) + \cos(8\pi/7) + \cos(12\pi/7)] \right) \] Using the identity for the sum of cosines of angles in a heptagon, \(\cos(2\pi/7) + \cos(4\pi/7) + \cos(6\pi/7) = -1/2\), we simplify the expression: \[ \frac{1}{8} \left( 9 - 4(-1/2) + (-1/2) \right) = \frac{1}{8} \left( 9 + 2 - 0.5 \right) = \frac{10.5}{8} = \frac{21}{16} \] Thus, the sum \(S = \sin^4(\pi/7) + \sin^4(2\pi/7) + \sin^4(3\pi/7) = \frac{21}{16}\). Multiplying by 112: \[ 112 \times \frac{21}{16} = 7 \times 21 = 147 \] Finally, taking modulo 100: \[ 147 \mod 100 = 47 \] The answer is \(\boxed{47}\).
